@flexiarg peripherals/read-only-first-then-extend
@title Read-Only First, Then Extend
@sigils [👁/觀]
@audience peripheral designers, agent implementers, operators
@tone foundational
@style pattern
@keywords read-only, blast-radius, escalation, observer, pair, collaborate, consent-gate, presence, follow, scout, write-permission
@references [peripherals/constrained-execution-envelope peripherals/inhabitation-feeds-evolution peripherals/surface-earns-inhabitation peripherals/split-transport-from-embodiment]

! conclusion: A new peripheral's first instantiation should be read-only — observing, displaying, not writing. Write capability is added in a separate, later instantiation once observation has revealed what writes actually need to look like.

  + context: You are about to instantiate a new peripheral. The mission
    describes both observation and action: see other agents' cursors AND
    move your own cursor visible to them; receive bells AND ring them;
    watch the War Machine state AND inject judgements.

  + IF:
    The peripheral, if fully implemented, would both read shared state
    and write to it — affecting other agents, other operators, or
    persistent substrate.

  + HOWEVER:
    Writing is irreversible in ways that observing is not. A misshapen
    observation produces a confusing display the operator can ignore. A
    misshapen write corrupts a substrate, surprises a collaborator,
    triggers downstream cascades, or — in the worst case — competes with
    another agent for write-ownership the peripheral did not know it
    was claiming. The full peripheral's blast radius is large; the
    read-only subset's blast radius is zero.

    + FAILURE-MODES:
      - Write-before-shape-known: the peripheral writes events whose
        schema turns out to be wrong because nobody observed what the
        right schema would be. Now there is committed wire data to
        migrate.
      - Bidirectional from day one: the peripheral both reads and writes
        in v1, so any bug is in the bidirectional interaction surface,
        which is the hardest possible bug to debug.
      - Consent-elided: the peripheral's writes cross a consent boundary
        that nobody noticed because the design was focused on the
        round-trip experience, not on the per-direction implications.
      - Read-only as permanent: the converse failure — building the
        observer and never extending it, so the peripheral never closes
        its loop and never feeds the Baldwin cycle. Read-only is a
        first step, not a terminal state.

  + THEN:
    Instantiate the peripheral in three escalating stages, each with its
    own checkpoint and consent step:

    1. **Observer stage (read-only)** — the peripheral subscribes to the
       transport, renders presence/state in the embodiment surface, and
       writes nothing back. The operator/agent can see what the
       peripheral does and decide whether the observation is
       well-shaped. Blast radius: zero. Exit criterion: the observation
       is informative enough that "what writes should look like" becomes
       discoverable.
    2. **Pair stage (consent-gated write)** — the peripheral can propose
       writes, but each write requires explicit consent (a confirmation
       step, a key press, a bell-ack roundtrip). Blast radius: bounded
       by per-write consent. Exit criterion: the writes have shown a
       stable schema and the consent prompts are no longer surprising.
    3. **Collaborate stage (envelope-bounded write)** — the peripheral
       writes autonomously within a documented envelope (specific
       targets, specific event types, specific time windows). Consent is
       no longer per-write but per-envelope-grant. Blast radius: bounded
       by the envelope. Exit criterion: documented stable behaviour
       under autonomous operation.

    Each stage is a separate landing. You do not ship Pair without first
    landing Observer; you do not ship Collaborate without first landing
    Pair. Each stage produces its own evidence and its own Baldwin-loop
    data that informs the next stage's design.

  + BECAUSE:
    The escalation matches the natural epistemic order. To know what
    writes should look like, you need to observe what is being read and
    where the gaps are. To know what consent should feel like, you need
    to have made some writes and noticed the friction. To know what
    envelope is safe, you need to have made consent-gated writes long
    enough to see the failure modes.

    Skipping stages means designing later stages on speculation rather
    than observation. Speculative design is exactly what the peripheral
    framing is meant to displace.

    The pattern also matches the consent-gate-as-locus-of-WM-I4
    principle: the consent step is a first-class artefact, and the
    migration from supervised to autonomous is the swap of operator-
    consent for autopen-consent at a single, documented location. That
    swap is only safe after the operator has spent enough time
    consenting to know what they are signing off on. The Pair stage is
    where that knowledge accumulates.

    Crucially, "read-only first" is not the same as "don't ship anything
    until you understand everything." Observer is a real shipped
    peripheral — it has inhabitation, it produces value (the display is
    used), it generates Baldwin-loop data. It is just a peripheral whose
    capability is exactly read, no more.

    + evidence: M-emacs-cursor-peripheral (2026-05-24, codex-8): Codex
      proposed instantiating the cursor peripheral as read-only first
      (display other agents' cursors without broadcasting own position),
      then pair (broadcast own position with explicit opt-in), then
      collaborate (autonomous co-presence). Each stage maps to a
      separate landing with separate consent semantics.

    + evidence: crdt.el (Emacs CRDT): the canonical workflow has
      "follow" mode (you observe another user's cursor) as a distinct
      capability from "share" mode (you broadcast your own state).
      Follow is strictly safer to enable; share requires more trust.

    + evidence: M-war-machine-pilot (futon3c, DERIVE 2026-05-24): the
      mission's Pilot-I1 (consent-gated-substantive-action) and its
      envelope design (direct write within envelope; consent-gate at
      substantive granularity) implicitly assumes a path from observer
      to pair to collaborate. Making the stages explicit clarifies
      what "v0 audit by re-invoked claude-9" actually validates.

    + evidence: futon3c blackboard backpressure
      (project_blackboard_backpressure, agent memory): hot paths
      synchronously block on emacsclient. A peripheral that wrote into
      those paths before observing the backpressure topology would
      cascade. Observer-first surfaces the backpressure topology BEFORE
      the peripheral takes a write-position in it.

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - For every new peripheral, define the three stages explicitly in
      the mission's IDENTIFY or MAP phase. Each stage gets its own
      success criteria and its own bell-ready landing.
    - When estimating timeline, treat the three stages as three
      missions' worth of work, not one. Observer alone can ship in
      hours; Pair takes days; Collaborate takes weeks or months.
    - For M-war-machine-pilot specifically: the v0 pilot should be the
      Observer-stage version of the WM peripheral. The audit by
      claude-9-re-invoked validates Observer shape. Pair and Collaborate
      stages are follow-on missions.
    - If an operator asks for "v1 with everything," push back with the
      stage breakdown. The conversation about which stage maps to which
      timeline is itself a Baldwin-loop event.
